{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657601"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:31:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20577"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20577"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.96,0,0.04,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93706"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13454"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76916"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"12502"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12797"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32120"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32123"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93706"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAtherosclerosis is a progressive inflammatory disease characterised by lipid accumulation in the arterial wall. The earliest visible lesions in this process contain lipid-filled macrophages.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes these early atherosclerotic lesions?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Fibrous plaques","Fatty streaks","Complicated lesions","Atheromatous plaques","Calcified nodules"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe earliest visible atherosclerotic lesions are \u003Cstrong\u003Efatty streaks\u003C/strong\u003E. These lesions appear as yellowish streaks on the luminal surface of arteries and consist primarily of lipid-laden macrophages called foam cells. Foam cells form when macrophages ingest oxidized low-density lipoproteins via scavenger receptors and accumulate cholesterol esters.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrous plaques\u003C/strong\u003E - These represent a more advanced stage of atherosclerosis, characterized by a fibrous cap containing smooth muscle cells and collagen overlying a lipid-rich core.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplicated lesions\u003C/strong\u003E - These are advanced atherosclerotic lesions that have undergone additional changes such as calcification, ulceration, hemorrhage, or thrombosis.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtheromatous plaques\u003C/strong\u003E - These are more advanced lesions with a well-defined lipid core and fibrous cap, representing progression beyond the fatty streak stage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcified nodules\u003C/strong\u003E - These represent a late stage of atherosclerosis where calcium deposits have formed within the plaque.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFatty streaks can develop in early childhood and may either progress to more advanced lesions or regress. They do not cause symptoms but represent the initial pathological change in the atherosclerotic process. The progression from fatty streaks to more advanced lesions involves continued lipid accumulation, smooth muscle cell migration and proliferation, and extracellular matrix deposition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fatty streaks are the earliest visible atherosclerotic lesions and contain lipid-filled macrophages (foam cells).","Foam cells form when macrophages ingest oxidized low-density lipoproteins via scavenger receptors.","Fatty streaks can progress to more advanced atherosclerotic lesions but may also regress in some cases."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotan Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 11; pages 498"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76916"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20577"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76916","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76916"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-22T09:00:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T09:01:35+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13454"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93706"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4914"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Blood vessels","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-15T20:38:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12502"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Atherosclerosis","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-22T08:40:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-22T08:40:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"10"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}